{{Infobox Bilateral relations|Republic of China–Latvia|Latvia|Taiwan}}

'''Sino-Latvian relations''' dates back to 1923 when the [[Republic of China (1912–49)|Republic of China]] recognized [[Latvia]] ''de jure''. After the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[Occupation of the Baltic states|occupation of Latvia in 1940]], the ROC is one of the few countries that did not recognize Latvia's incorporation into the Soviet Union. {{Citation needed|date=June 2017}}

Latvia never re-established relations with the ROC after restoring its independence in 1991 and later established relations with the [[China|People's Republic of China]].<ref>http://www.upi.com/Archives/1992/09/17/Despite-Beijings-displeasure-Latvia-plans-to-establish-ties-with-Taiwan/3385716702400/</ref> However, in its place, Latvia operates the [[Taipei Economic and Cultural Representative Office]] in [[Riga]] and the Taipei Mission in the Republic of Latvia in [[Taipei]].

