'''''Midwest Herald''''' is a weekly [[investigative journalism]] [[newspaper]] published in [[Nigeria]].<ref name=":0">{{cite news|url=https://allafrica.com/stories/200506010752.html|title=Nigeria: A Turbulent Debut for Midwest Herald|last1=Okoli|first1=Tunde|date=30 May 2005|work=AllAfrica.com|accessdate=20 November 2018|archive-url=http://archive.is/8qpDV|archive-date=19 October 2012|url-access=subscription}}&mdash;The archived version is complete, while the live version available without a subscription is incomplete.</ref>

''Midwest Herald'' began normal publication on April 22, 2005; its name as a pilot publication was ''Weekend People''.<ref name=":0" />  It very quickly encountered challenges - after a story critical of Nigeria's first lady appeared, the publisher of the ''Midwest Herald'', Orobosa Omo-Ojo, was detained on charges of [[sedition]], and the newspaper's office was sealed by police.<ref>{{cite news |title=Police arrest and detain newspaper publisher |url=https://ifex.org/nigeria/2005/05/05/police_arrest_and_detain_newspaper/ |accessdate=15 November 2018 |work=IFEX |agency=MRA/IFEX |date=5 May 2005}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Publisher under arrest after “Greedy Stella” Obasanjo story |url=http://www.irinnews.org/fr/node/221841 |accessdate=15 November 2018 |work=IRIN News |date=9 May 2005}}</ref>  Orobosa was released without formal charges 12 days later.<ref>{{cite news |title=Detained newspaper publisher released |url=https://ifex.org/nigeria/2005/05/20/detained_newspaper_publisher_released/ |accessdate=15 November 2018 |work=IFEX |agency=MRA/IFEX |date=20 May 2005}}</ref>

The publication was noted as being defunct in a 2016 news report.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.tribuneonlineng.com/10334/|title=Edo 2016: The ripples over Breach of Trust|last=Aluko|first=Banji|date=28 July 2016|work=Nigerian Tribune|access-date=20 November 2018}}</ref>

